<td><span class="IPA nowrap" lang="und-Latn-fonipa" title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)">[kai<span class="wrap"> </span>zi˩]</span>
</td>
<td>'chopsticks'
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>Hakka, as well as numerous other Chinese varieties such as Min and Cantonese, prefers the verb <span class="IPA nowrap" lang="und-Latn-fonipa" title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)">[kɔŋ˧˩]</span> <span lang="zh-Hant"><a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E8%AC%9B#Traditional_Chinese" class="extiw" title="wikt:講">講</a></span> when referring to 'saying', rather than the Mandarin <span lang="zh">說</span>; <i><span lang="zh-Latn">shuō</span></i> (Hakka pronunciation: <span class="IPA nowrap" lang="und-Latn-fonipa" title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)">[sɔt˩]</span>).
</p><p>Hakka uses <span class="IPA nowrap" lang="und-Latn-fonipa" title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)">[sit˥]</span> <span lang="zh"><a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E9%A3%9F#Chinese" class="extiw" title="wikt:食">食</a></span>, like Cantonese <span class="IPA nowrap" lang="und-Latn-fonipa" title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)">[sɪk˨]</span> for the verb 'to eat' and <span lang="zh-Hant"><a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E9%A3%B2#Traditional_Chinese" class="extiw" title="wikt:飲">飲</a></span> <span class="IPA nowrap" lang="und-Latn-fonipa" title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)">[jɐm˧˥]</span> (Hakka <span class="IPA nowrap" lang="und-Latn-fonipa" title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)">[jim˧˩]</span>) for 'to drink', unlike Mandarin which prefers <span title="Chinese-language romanization"><i lang="zh-Latn">chī</i></span> <span lang="zh"><a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E5%90%83#Chinese" class="extiw" title="wikt:吃">吃</a></span> (Hakka <span class="IPA nowrap" lang="und-Latn-fonipa" title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)">[kʰiɛt˩]</span>) as 'to eat' and <span lang="zh">喝</span>; <i><span lang="zh-Latn">hē</span></i> (Hakka <span class="IPA nowrap" lang="und-Latn-fonipa" title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)">[hɔt˩]</span>) as 'to drink' where the meanings in Hakka are different, 'to stutter' and 'to be thirsty' respectively.
</p>
